## The First Storyteller

**Y'ffre**, also known as Jephre in the Imperial pantheon, is one of the most important yet least understood **Aedra** among Imperial scholars. Where **Akatosh** gave the world time and **Magnus** gave it magic, Y'ffre gave it form and stability. Before his sacrifice, the world had no fixed rules: beings changed shape at will, the land flowed like water, and nothing retained its nature from one moment to the next.

It was Y'ffre who, first among the et'Ada, voluntarily transformed himself into the laws of nature. His body became the rules governing the growth of plants, the cycle of seasons, and the fixity of biological forms. By telling himself, by becoming the first story, he created the narrative framework within which all existence on **Nirn** unfolds. This is why the **Bosmer** call him the Storyteller or the Narrator.

## The Chaos of the Ooze

Before Y'ffre's intervention, the earliest inhabitants of what would become **Valenwood** existed in a state of perpetual flux known as the **Ooze**. This primordial soup of potentiality saw beings constantly transforming, unable to hold a stable form. An Elf could become a tree, then a river, then a deer, without control or will of their own. It was an existence of absolute terror and confusion.

The Bosmer accounts describe this period as a collective nightmare. Without a fixed form, there was no identity. Without identity, there was no community. The proto-Bosmer were prisoners of a constant flux that denied them any permanence or meaning. Madness threatened every consciousness, drowned in a torrent of involuntary transformations.

It was from this primordial horror that Y'ffre saved them. By sacrificing himself to become the laws of nature, he anchored forms and gave each being a stable identity. Trees remained trees. Elves remained Elves. The world finally acquired narrative coherence, a continuity that allowed for stable consciousness and persistent memory.

## The Green Pact

In exchange for this gift of stability, Y'ffre imposed on the **Bosmer** a sacred oath: the **Green Pact**. This pact forbids the Wood Elves from consuming or destroying any plant matter. They may not cut trees, cultivate edible plants, or use wood for construction or fire. In return, the forest of Valenwood protects them and provides everything they need.

The implications of this pact are considerable. The Bosmer are obligately carnivorous, feeding exclusively on meat and animal products. Their constructions are made of bone, leather, shell, and other non-plant materials. Their most famous cities are not built but grown: they are giant trees shaped by Y'ffre's own will to shelter his children.

The Pact also includes the **Meat Mandate**, a tradition requiring the Bosmer to consume the bodies of their fallen enemies in combat. This cannibalistic practice horrifies other cultures, but for the Bosmer it is a sacred duty to Y'ffre. To fail to honor the Meat Mandate would be an offense as grave as felling a living tree.

## Valenwood, Y'ffre's Garden

**Valenwood** is far more than a simple forest province: it is Y'ffre's living garden, an ecosystem entirely shaped by divine will. Every tree, every plant, every waterway bears the Storyteller's imprint. The forest is conscious, responsive, and actively protects its Bosmer inhabitants against invaders.

The **Graht-Oaks** are the most spectacular expression of Y'ffre's power. These titanic trees, some reaching hundreds of meters in height, move slowly through the forest, carrying entire cities on their branches. **Falinesti**, the ancient walking capital of the Bosmer, was the greatest of these tree-cities, a living wonder that traveled across Valenwood with the seasons.

The disappearance of Falinesti at the start of the **Fourth Era** was seen by many as a sign of the waning of Y'ffre's influence. Some Bosmer believe the tree-city sank into the roots of the world to protect itself from a coming threat. Others think that the growing violation of the Green Pact by newer generations has weakened the bond between Y'ffre and Valenwood.

## The Canticle and the Wild Hunt

Y'ffre's power also manifests in two major mystical phenomena. The **Canticle** is the ability of certain blessed Bosmer to communicate directly with the forest, to sing to the trees and understand Y'ffre's will as expressed in the growth of plants and the whisper of wind through the leaves. The Cantors are Y'ffre's priests and prophets, capable of shaping vegetation without destroying it.

The **Wild Hunt**, by contrast, represents the most terrifying aspect of Y'ffre's power. When the Bosmer are driven to despair, they can invoke an ancient ritual that returns them to the state of the original Ooze. They abandon their fixed forms and become shape-shifting monsters, a nightmare pack that destroys everything in its path. Every Wild Hunt is irreversible: participants never recover their original forms.

This duality between the order of the Green Pact and the chaos of the Wild Hunt reflects Y'ffre's very nature. The Storyteller did not eliminate the Ooze; he merely contained it beneath the surface of reality. And when that containment is deliberately broken, the ancient horror resurges with a violence proportional to the time it spent under constraint.

## The Living Legacy

Y'ffre's influence extends far beyond Valenwood. Every ecosystem on **Nirn** functions according to the rules he established. The growth of plants, the migration of animals, the cycle of seasons — all of this is the Storyteller's work, his story continuing to unfold even though he himself has dissolved into the natural laws.

The **Wyrd**, nature witches found throughout western Tamriel, venerate Y'ffre under various names and seek to maintain the balance of his story. The **Druids** of High Rock, descendants of ancient Bretons who rejected civilization, also follow his teachings, though their interpretation differs considerably from that of the Bosmer.

For faithful Bosmer, Y'ffre is not a distant and silent god. He is present in every leaf that grows, every river that flows, every cycle of life and death in the forest. His story continues, and every living being is a character within it. Death itself is merely a change of chapter in the Storyteller's endless tale.
